<p><strong>INSTRUCTIONS</strong>: Choose units and enter the following:</p>=
=20
<ul>=20
 <li>(<strong>a</strong>) Length of Side a&nbsp; (top parallel line)&nbsp;<=
/li>=20
 <li>(<strong>b</strong>) Length of Side b (bottome parallel line)</li>=20
 <li>(<strong>c</strong>) Length of Side c (right side)</li>=20
 <li>(<strong>d</strong>) Length of Side d (left side)</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p><strong>Angles of Trapezoid (A,B,C,D)</strong>: The calculator returns t=
he angles in degrees.&nbsp; However, these can be automatically converted t=
o compatible units via the pull-down menu.</p>=20
<h3>The Math / Science</h3>=20
<p><strong>Trapezoid </strong>or <strong>trapezium</strong>, as it's known =
in the UK,&nbsp; is a quadrilateral with two parallel sides, shown as the t=
op and bottom in this diagram.&nbsp; The height of a trapezoid (h) is the p=
erpendicular distance between the two parallel sides.</p>=20
<p>This method uses Heron's formula to compute the area of the triangles si=
des.</p>=20
<p><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://www.vcalc.com/attachments/b5cfda33-5958-11e=
e-b65f-bc764e203090/trapezoid-height.PNG" style=3D"height:202px; width:600p=
x"></p>=20
<p>The method then uses the formula for the area of a triangle, A =3D 1/2 *=
 x * h, to compute the height (h).</p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-left:40px">h =3D 2*A / x</p>=20
<p>where:</p>=20
<ul>=20
 <li>h =3D height of the triangle and therefor the trapezoid</li>=20
 <li>A =3D area of the triangle</li>=20
 <li>x =3D base of the triangle which is equal to the difference of the two=
 parallel lines (x =3D b-a)</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>With h, sines and cosines, the angles can be computed.</p>=20
<p><a href=3D"https://www.vcalc.com/wikiclip/?uuid=3D492a0ce2-5968-11ee-b65=
